Windows build can fail before Maven starts
File: mvnw.cmd:92
When it breaks: running mvnw.cmd in some Windows environments (I reproduced this here: Cannot index into a null array).
How it breaks under the hood: script accesses (Get-Item $MAVEN_M2_PATH).Target[0]; if Target is null, PowerShell throws and wrapper exits before launching Maven.
Solution: harden null handling:
check Target exists and has items before indexing
fallback to "$MAVEN_M2_PATH/wrapper/dists" directly
Why this works: it removes a fragile symlink/junction assumption and guarantees path resolution.
Build portability risk from Java 25 requirement
File: pom.xml:30
When it breaks: CI/dev machines on Java 17/21 (common LTS) fail to compile/start.
How: Maven compiler and Spring runtime target java.version=25; older JDKs reject bytecode/source level.
Solution: use LTS (21) unless Java 25 features are required; enforce via Maven Enforcer plugin.
Why: keeps toolchain consistent across environments and avoids startup/build outages.
Data inconsistency due to split transactions in POST flow
Files: WorkoutController.java:31, WorkoutController.java:32, WorkoutService.java:19, GoalService.java:24
When: workout save succeeds but goal update fails (DB lock/timeout/etc).
How: each service method is separately transactional; first commit can complete before second starts/fails.
Solution: create one application-service method with a single @Transactional boundary calling both operations.
Why: atomicity (all succeed or all rollback).
Multi-instance race can create multiple goal rows
Files: GoalService.java:45, FitnessGoal.java:11
When: two app nodes start/update simultaneously and no goal exists yet.
How: synchronized only protects threads inside one JVM; other instances can insert concurrently.
Solution: enforce DB uniqueness for singleton goal (e.g., fixed key/unique column) and upsert/retry on conflict.
Why: database-level constraint is the only cross-instance lock authority.
Lock contention can throw 500s under load
Files: FitnessRepo.java:18, GoalService.java:40
When: concurrent updates hold PESSIMISTIC_WRITE lock too long.
How: waiting transactions can timeout/deadlock -> JPA exception -> 500.
Solution: set lock timeout and add retry/backoff for transient lock failures; optionally switch to optimistic flow with @Version retry.
Why: converts lock spikes from hard failures to controlled retries.
Exception handler can itself fail and misclassify client errors
File: GlobalExceptionHandler.java:21, GlobalExceptionHandler.java:27
When: object-level validation errors occur, or service throws IllegalArgumentException.
How: cast to FieldError can throw ClassCastException; broad RuntimeException maps client mistakes to 500.
Solution: handle ObjectError safely, add explicit handlers for IllegalArgumentException (400) and not-found (404), keep generic 500 fallback last.
Why: prevents error-handler crashes and improves API reliability/observability.
Unbounded fetch can exhaust memory at scale
File: WorkoutService.java:39
When: workout table grows large.
How: findAll() loads full dataset into memory; long GC pauses / OOM risk.
Solution: paginate (Pageable) in API and repository calls.
Why: bounded memory and predictable response time.
Data loss on restart (in-memory DB)
File: application.properties:2
When: app restarts/crashes/deploys.
How: jdbc:h2:mem: data exists only in process memory.
Solution: use persistent DB (PostgreSQL/MySQL) for non-dev; keep H2 only in dev profile.
Why: state survives process/system failures.
Production exposure risk if H2 console enabled
File: application.properties:7
When: deployed with same config.
How: DB console endpoint exposed; unauthorized access surface.
Solution: disable by default, enable only in dev profile with network restrictions.
Why: reduces attack surface and accidental data tampering.
